final_answer("In theoretical computer science, LIFO (Last-In-First-Out) and FIFO (First-In-First-Out) describe the order in which elements are removed from a collection.

1. **LIFO (Stack):** The most recently added item is the first to be removed. Think of a stack of plates; you only take the one from the top. In Java, this is implemented via `java.util.Stack`.
   Example:
   ```java
   import java.util.Stack;
   Stack<String> stack = new Stack<>();
   stack.push("A");
   stack.push("B");
   stack.pop(); // Removes 'B'
   ```

2. **FIFO (Queue):** The oldest item is the first to be removed. Think of a line of people at a bus stop; the first person in line is the first to board. In Java, `java.util.Queue` is an interface, commonly implemented by `java.util.LinkedList`.
   Example:
   ```java
   import java.util.LinkedList;
   import java.util.Queue;
   Queue<String> queue = new LinkedList<>();
   queue.add("A");
   queue.add("B");
   queue.poll(); // Removes 'A'
   ```")
