final_answer("Yes, it is possible to determine the drive letter of a USB flash drive using .NET. You can use the `System.IO.DriveInfo.GetDrives()` method and filter the results by `DriveType.Removable`.

Example 1: Listing all removable drives
```csharp
using System;
using System.IO;
using System.Linq;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        DriveInfo[] allDrives = DriveInfo.GetDrives();
        var usbDrives = allDrives.Where(d => d.DriveType == DriveType.Removable);

        foreach (DriveInfo d in usbDrives)
        {
            Console.WriteLine("USB drive found! drive letter {0}", d.Name);
        }
    }
}
```

Example 2: Assigning the first ready USB drive to a variable
```csharp
using System;
using System.IO;
using System.Linq;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        var usbDrive = GetUsbDrive();
        if (usbDrive == null)
        {
            Console.WriteLine("No USB drives detected.");
        }
        else
        {
            Console.WriteLine("Found USB drive: " + usbDrive.Name);
        }
    }

    static DriveInfo GetUsbDrive()
    {
        DriveInfo[] allDrives = DriveInfo.GetDrives();
        return allDrives.FirstOrDefault(d => d.DriveType == DriveType.Removable && d.IsReady);
    }
}
```

Note: `DriveType.Removable` identifies drives that can be removed from the system, which includes USB flash drives. While this is usually sufficient, it doesn't strictly guarantee the hardware is a USB device (e.g., it could be an SD card reader), but for most installation scenarios, this is the standard approach.")
