```cpp
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>

std::vector<int> shared_elements(std::vector<int> list1, std::vector<int> list2) {
    std::vector<int> shared;
    for (auto i: list1) {
        // Check if element i exists in list2 and not in shared
        if (std::find(list2.begin(), list2.end(), i) != list2.end() &&
            std::find(shared.begin(), shared.end(), i) == shared.end()) {
            shared.push_back(i);
        }
    }
    // Sorting without built-in function
    for (int i = 0; i < shared.size(); i++) {
        int min_index = i;
        for (int j = i+1; j < shared.size(); j++) {
            if (shared[j] < shared[min_index]) {
                min_index = j;
            }
        }
        std::swap(shared[i], shared[min_index]);
    }
    return shared;
}
```

This version uses the STL `std::find` function to search for an element in the vectors, because C++ does not have an equivalent to Python's `in` keyword for list containment check. It also uses `std::swap` to swap elements in the list. Note that the `auto` keyword used in the range-for loop automatically deduces the type of the variable being declared.

Also keep in mind that C++ doesn't have a native list type. Instead, we are using `std::vector` as a stand-in for Python's list. The C++ standard library `vector` class is a dynamic array, while a list in Python is more similar to a linked list.")
