Thought: I need to implement the LCM logic in Java. I'll start by writing the source code to a file named `LcmPairs.java`. I will include the `gcd` helper method, the `lcm` method, and the `pairLCM` logic as requested, including validation for positive integers.
<code>
content = """public class LcmPairs {
    // Method to find gcd of a and b
    public static int gcd(int a, int b) {
        if (b == 0)
            return a;
        return gcd(b, a % b);
    }

    // Method to find lcm of a and b
    public static int lcm(int a, int b) {
        if (a == 0 || b == 0) return 0;
        int gcd = gcd(a, b);
        // Use division first to prevent overflow before multiplication
        return Math.abs(a / gcd * b);
    }

    public static int[] pairLCM(int[] inputArray) {
        if (inputArray == null || inputArray.length == 0)
            return new int[0];

        // Error handling for negative numbers and zeros
        for (int i = 0; i < inputArray.length; i++) {
            if (inputArray[i] <= 0) {
                throw new IllegalArgumentException("Input array should contain only positive integers.");
            }
        }

        int len = inputArray.length;
        int[] outputArray = new int[(len + 1) / 2];
        for (int i = 0; i < len / 2; i++) {
            outputArray[i] = lcm(inputArray[2 * i], inputArray[2 * i + 1]);
        }

        // If input array length is odd, copy the last number
        if (len % 2 != 0) {
            outputArray[outputArray.length - 1] = inputArray[len - 1];
        }

        return outputArray;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            int[] input = {12, 15, 18};
            int[] result = pairLCM(input);
            System.out.print("Result: ");
            for (int i : result) System.out.print(i + " ");
            System.out.println();
        } catch (Exception e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}"""
